column7: Most people aren't going to give long-winded, superfluous responses. The more curt, to-the-point responses definitely reflect a more human-likeness.
column8: Most, if not all, chatbots blindly agree with you on everything. They're all seemingly afraid of going against the grain and disagreeing with the user.

column7: I mostly stuck to the instruction set of points that listed some behaviors of so-called "AI" (chatbots). And if I'm being honest, both chatbots always came off as VERY much chatbots. That said, there were different degrees of this in each of the five pairs. Repetition always stuck out to me to make the chatbot be more "chatbot". So if one had less repetition than the other I rated it more human-like. I also found the more succinct and to the point responses to be more human-like than the long wandering paragraphs.
column8: I do not use chatbots but they're obviously always going to be derivative of the content they are trained on and can never be human-like and natural in that respect. I think the instruction set laid out that list of six points well that chatbots are prone to. Limiting these would "help". Also, specific to this type of interaction; People tend to let their doctor take control of a conversation and just answer the question without extra.

column7: I went by what sound realistic. Overly chatty patients felt like a "bot giveaway" like the ones that wanted to tell me a whole story instead of getting to the point. Also, patients that sounded overly knowledgeable or overly paranoid about certain treatments.
column8: Instead of having more of a back and forth, it felt like they wanted to spill too much at once, almost like they wanted too much to convince me that they were human. Also, they seemed more sure of themselves than the "human" ones did.  I kind of felt like there wasn't much middle ground...they were either too chatty or it felt like you had to pull information out of them, no in between.

column7: I was looking the things that were recommended, the conciseness, the technicality, how overly wordy the messages where. But also, the grammar. Things like em dashes and grammar that people typically don't use when typing casually. I was also looking for strange confusions and things that were very prevalent in the final conversation I had which is why I did a "Tie" on that one. I couldn't bring myself to choose B, even if it was less wordy. It was clearly mechanical and speaking in a way that is not typical of a human being.
column8: Sometimes the grammar was just too perfect, people are more sloppy than that. They hesitate, they use slang, they listen and ask open ended questions instead of immediately pushing back and getting confused in the process. The final chat I had where I chose Tie was because they both felt mechanical, both had too perfect of grammar, and one of them seemed confused in a way that made no sense and it was being overly cheery  while pushing back against what I was saying in a way that was too wordy and not more eager to learn about what the possibilities of what I was recommending where. They were talking about chemicals when I was talking about physical therapy, they forgot they told me they took Tylenol, it was just really messy. I couldn't in good conscience choose anything other than a Tie for that one because it felt very AI to me.

column7: I use the criteria of what sounded more natural to me. I thought about how people are when they go to the doctor. I thought about how open most people are and myself with information to tell the doctor. The answers needed to be natural and not say so much but enough to get treatment.
column8: The human like trait that was missing was  over expanding answers. You did need to give the doctor enough information but not extra unneeded information. Instead of the chatbot saying this pain is tearing me up , the chatbot would say these silly pains are tearing me up.  Some of the words was not human like and came out robotize, and so much information at once.
